In [[English history]], '''Conformists''' were those whose [[Religion|religious practices]] conformed with the requirements of the [[Act of Uniformity]] and so were in concert with the [[Established Church]], the [[Church of England]], as opposed to those of [[Nonconformists]] whose practices were not acceptable to the Church of England.

In a more general (small "c") sense, ''conformists'' are those who attempt to comply with all [[Norm|societal norms]], generally so as to not stand out in any way and hence be subject to potential ridicule or other [[Social control|social sanctions]].

